  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1964, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Direct Vs Indirect CFO$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Most companies present operating cash flow the indirect way. Contrast the direct and indirect methods for the operating section, and walk me through how you would reconcile the two for a company with 1,000 of net income, 100 of depreciation, a 40 increase in receivables, and a 25 increase in payables.$x$, $x$["Indirect Starts At Net Income Adjusts Noncash And Working Capital", "Direct Lists Gross Cash Receipts And Cash Payments", "Both Produce Identical Total CFO", "Depreciation Added Back Only Indirect", "AR Up Uses Cash AP Up Frees Cash", "Reconciliation Schedule Required Even If Direct Used", "Cash From Customers Equals Revenue Less AR Increase"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Both methods land on the exact same operating cash flow - they just get there differently. The indirect method starts at net income and adjusts it: add back non-cash items like depreciation, then layer in working capital changes. The direct method instead lists actual cash flows - cash collected from customers, cash paid to suppliers, to employees, for taxes. Almost everyone uses indirect because it ties cleanly to the income statement and balance sheet, and even firms that present direct must disclose an indirect reconciliation. For your numbers: indirect gives 1,000 net income, plus 100 depreciation, minus the 40 receivables build because that revenue was not yet collected, plus the 25 payables increase because I held onto cash I owe - so CFO is 1,085. The direct view is the same total: cash from customers is roughly revenue minus the 40 AR increase, and cash to suppliers is purchases plus the 25 I deferred by stretching payables. Depreciation never appears directly because it is non-cash. The reconciliation is just walking net income to that 1,085 line by line.$x$),
(1965, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Selling A Business Unit$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company sells one of its divisions for 500 of cash. The division's net assets on the books are 300, the tax rate is 25 percent, and it qualifies as a discontinued operation. Walk me through how this sale flows through all three statements, including the gain, the tax, the cash, and the discontinued-operations presentation.$x$, $x$["Pretax Gain Equals Proceeds Less Net Book Value", "Gain Reported Net Of Tax In Discontinued Operations", "Tax On Gain Reduces Cash And Equity", "Net Assets Removed From Balance Sheet", "Cash Inflow In Investing Section", "Prior Periods Reclassified To Disc Ops", "Equity Up By After Tax Gain"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Start with the gain: proceeds of 500 less net book value of 300 gives a 200 pretax gain. Because it qualifies as a discontinued operation, this does not sit in continuing operations - the entire result of that division, including the 200 gain, gets pulled out and shown on one line, net of tax, as income from discontinued operations. So the gain hits the income statement at 200 less 25 percent tax, which is 150 after tax, and the 50 of tax is the related expense. On the balance sheet, the division's assets and liabilities come off - the 300 of net assets is removed - and cash goes up. Equity rises by the 150 after-tax gain through retained earnings. On the cash flow statement, the gain is a non-cash item for operating purposes, so under the indirect method I back the 200 gain out of operating cash flow to avoid double counting, and the actual 500 of proceeds shows up in investing. The tax of 50 is a cash outflow. Critically, prior-period income statements get recast so the division is shown as discontinued there too, making continuing operations comparable.$x$),
(1966, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$FX Transaction Gain Loss$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$This is about a foreign-currency transaction, not translating a subsidiary. A US company with the dollar as its functional currency sells goods to a French customer for 100,000 euros on credit, when the euro is worth 1.10 dollars. By the time the customer pays, the euro is worth 1.05. Walk me through the accounting and where the gain or loss lands.$x$, $x$["Record Receivable At Spot On Transaction Date", "Remeasure Monetary Item At Each Reporting Date", "FX Gain Or Loss Hits Net Income Not OCI", "Euro Weakened So Transaction Loss Of 5000", "Distinct From Translation CTA In Equity", "Revenue Fixed At Original Spot Rate", "Settlement Difference Realized In Earnings"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The key thing is that this is a transaction exposure on a monetary asset, so the gain or loss runs straight through net income - it does not park in OCI the way a translation adjustment does. On the sale date I record revenue and a receivable at the spot rate, so 100,000 euros at 1.10 is 110,000 dollars. Revenue is locked at that amount. The receivable, though, is a monetary item denominated in euros, so I remeasure it at each balance sheet date and at settlement using the current spot. When the customer pays, the euro has weakened to 1.05, so I collect 100,000 euros worth only 105,000 dollars. That 5,000 dollar shortfall is a foreign-currency transaction loss that hits the income statement, usually in other income or expense, not OCI. If a reporting date had fallen in between, I would have recognized the movement up to that point and the rest at settlement. Contrast this with translating a foreign subsidiary, where the cumulative translation adjustment sits in equity until the sub is sold. Here it is realized in earnings.$x$),
(1967, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Debt Modification Vs Extinguishment$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A struggling company renegotiates its term loan with lenders. Walk me through how you decide whether this is a debt modification or an extinguishment, why that distinction drives very different accounting, and where troubled-debt restructuring fits in.$x$, $x$["Ten Percent Cash Flow Test Drives Treatment", "Modification Adjusts Effective Rate No Immediate Gain Loss", "Extinguishment Books Gain Or Loss At Fair Value", "New Fees To Lender Capitalized Under Modification", "TDR When Lender Grants Concession To Troubled Borrower", "Old Costs Written Off On Extinguishment", "Carrying Value Vs Reacquisition Price"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The whole question turns on whether the terms changed enough to treat the old debt as gone. Under US GAAP the test is quantitative: I compare the present value of the cash flows under the new terms, discounted at the original effective rate, to the old debt's cash flows. If they differ by 10 percent or more, it is an extinguishment; if less, it is a modification. That distinction matters a lot. In a modification, there is no immediate gain or loss - I just compute a new effective interest rate that amortizes the existing carrying value over the new life, and any fees I pay the lender get capitalized into the balance and amortized. In an extinguishment, I treat the old debt as repaid and the new debt as freshly issued at fair value, so I book a gain or loss for the difference between the old carrying amount and the reacquisition value, and I write off any unamortized old issuance costs. Troubled-debt restructuring is the special case where the lender grants a concession specifically because the borrower is in financial trouble - the borrower may recognize a gain if the restructured cash flows fall below carrying value.$x$),
(1968, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Factoring Receivables$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company factors 100 of receivables to a bank to raise cash. Walk me through how you decide whether to account for this as a true sale or as a secured borrowing, and how that choice changes the balance sheet, the income statement, and the cash flow statement.$x$, $x$["Sale Requires Control Transfer And Derecognition", "Recourse And Continuing Involvement Suggest Borrowing", "True Sale Removes AR Books Loss On Sale", "Secured Borrowing Keeps AR Adds Liability", "CFO Effect Vs Financing Effect On Cash Flow", "Surrendering Effective Control Is The Test", "Discount Or Interest Expense Geography Differs"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The decision hinges on whether the company has truly surrendered control of the receivables. Under the derecognition rules, it is a sale only if the assets are isolated from the seller, the buyer can pledge or exchange them, and the seller no longer has effective control - things like a removable call. If those are met, it is a true sale: I take the 100 of receivables off the balance sheet, recognize the cash received, and book the difference between the cash and the carrying amount as a loss on sale running through the income statement. The cash inflow generally shows up in operating activities because it relates to receivables. If instead the deal has full recourse or the company keeps meaningful continuing involvement, it fails sale treatment and becomes a secured borrowing: the receivables stay on the books, I record a liability for the cash advanced, and the financing cost shows up as interest expense over time. There the cash inflow lands in financing. So the same transaction either shrinks the balance sheet and hits earnings now, or grosses it up with a new liability.$x$),
(1969, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Finance Lease Lessee Mechanics$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Put me on the lessee side of a finance lease with real numbers. A company leases equipment for 5 years with payments of 23 at year-end and a discount rate of 5 percent, giving a present value of about 100. Walk me through day-one recognition, the full first-year mechanics, and how the expense pattern and cash flow geography differ from an operating lease.$x$, $x$["Day One ROU Asset And Lease Liability At PV", "Interest On Liability Plus Straight Line Amortization", "Front Loaded Total Expense Versus Straight Line Operating", "Liability Reduced By Payment Less Interest", "Interest In CFO Principal In Financing", "Year One Interest 5 Amortization 20", "EBITDA Higher Under Finance Lease"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On day one I record a right-of-use asset and a lease liability both at the present value of the payments, so about 100. From there a finance lease splits into two expenses. First, interest on the liability: 5 percent on the 100 opening balance is 5 in year one. Second, amortization of the ROU asset, typically straight-line, so 100 over 5 years is 20 a year. Total first-year expense is 25. The 23 payment is allocated 5 to interest and 18 to principal, so the liability falls to about 82. Notice the expense is front-loaded - interest is highest early and declines as the balance shrinks, so total expense starts above and ends below the level 23. That contrasts with an operating lease, where I recognize a single straight-line lease expense of roughly 20 every year. The cash flow geography also differs: in a finance lease the interest portion sits in operating activities and the principal repayment of 18 sits in financing, whereas an operating lease keeps the whole payment in operating. Because amortization and interest live below EBITDA, a finance lease actually reports higher EBITDA than an operating lease for the same payment.$x$),
(1970, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Intercompany Inventory Profit$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A parent sells inventory to its wholly-owned subsidiary at a markup, and at year-end the subsidiary still holds some of that inventory unsold to outsiders. Walk me through the intercompany profit-in-inventory elimination on consolidation, why it is required, and how the answer changes if the sale had gone upstream from sub to parent with a minority interest present.$x$, $x$["Eliminate Unrealized Profit In Ending Inventory", "Profit Not Realized Until Sold To Third Party", "Reduce Inventory And Increase COGS On Consolidation", "Also Eliminate Full Intercompany Sales And COGS", "Downstream Charged Entirely To Parent", "Upstream Profit Allocated Between Parent And NCI", "Reverses When Inventory Sold Next Period"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Consolidated statements should look as if the group is one company, so profit earned by selling to yourself is not real until the goods leave the group. When the parent sells inventory to the sub at a markup and the sub still holds it at year-end, that markup is unrealized profit sitting inside ending inventory. On consolidation I eliminate it: I remove the full intercompany sale and the matching cost of goods sold so revenue is not double counted, then write the ending inventory back down to original cost, which increases consolidated COGS and lowers consolidated net income. Inventory on the balance sheet drops by that unrealized profit. It is purely a timing reversal - once the sub sells the goods to a third party next period, the profit becomes real and I reverse the adjustment. Direction matters when there is a non-controlling interest. In a downstream sale, parent to sub, the profit was earned by the parent, so the whole elimination is charged to the parent. In an upstream sale, sub to parent, the profit was earned by the partially-owned sub, so the elimination is split between the parent and the NCI in proportion to ownership.$x$),
(1971, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Treasury Stock Methods$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$This is about the accounting for repurchased shares, not diluted EPS. Contrast the cost method and the par-value method of accounting for treasury stock, walk me through what hits each equity account on buyback and resale, and explain why no gain or loss ever touches the income statement.$x$, $x$["Cost Method Single Contra Equity At Purchase Price", "Par Method Retires Shares Against Par And APIC", "Resale Above Cost Credits APIC Not Income", "Resale Below Cost Reduces APIC Then Retained Earnings", "No Gain Or Loss Through Income Statement", "Treasury Stock Reduces Total Equity", "Transactions With Owners Not Earnings"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Both methods reduce total equity, but they record it differently. Under the cost method, which is the more common one, I just debit a single treasury stock contra-equity account for whatever I paid, ignoring the original par and issue price. When I later reissue those shares, I credit treasury stock for the original cost; if I sell above cost the excess goes to additional paid-in capital, and if I sell below cost I reduce APIC from prior treasury transactions and then retained earnings if that is exhausted. Under the par-value method, I treat the buyback more like a retirement: I debit treasury stock for par, remove the related APIC from the original issuance, and route any difference to APIC or retained earnings immediately. The critical principle for both is that a company can never report a gain or loss on dealing in its own shares - these are transactions with owners, not earnings activities. So even if I buy back at 30 and resell at 50, that 20 spread runs entirely through paid-in capital and retained earnings, never through the income statement. Treasury stock simply sits as a reduction of stockholders equity.$x$),
(1972, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Earnings Management Red Flags$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You are screening a company whose reported earnings look great. Without access to anything beyond the public filings, what are the classic red flags that earnings quality is deteriorating or being managed, and which single comparison would you reach for first?$x$, $x$["Net income growing faster than cash from operations", "Receivables and inventory outgrowing revenue (rising DSO/DIO)", "Widening GAAP vs non-GAAP gap / recurring one-time charges", "Falling tax rate or reserve releases boosting EPS", "Capitalizing costs that used to be expensed", "First comparison: NI versus CFO trend over several years", "Revenue recognized ahead of cash / deferred revenue declining"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When earnings look too clean I go straight to the relationship between net income and cash from operations - if profit is climbing but operating cash flow is flat or falling, that divergence is the loudest red flag, because earnings can be managed with accruals but cash is harder to fake. Then I look at working capital: receivables or inventory growing faster than revenue usually means either channel stuffing or demand softening, both of which inflate today's earnings at the expense of tomorrow. I watch the tax rate, because a sudden drop or a reserve release can manufacture an EPS beat that has nothing to do with the business. I check whether costs that used to be expensed are now being capitalized, which flatters margins and shifts spend into investing. And I track the gap between GAAP and the company's adjusted numbers - if every quarter has a fresh restructuring or one-time charge, the one-timers are really recurring. The first comparison I always pull is the multi-year net income versus CFO trend, because it frames everything else.$x$),
(1973, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Cash EPS Versus GAAP EPS$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$An acquisitive industrials company trades on cash EPS, which it reports well above GAAP EPS. Walk me through what cash EPS actually adds back, why management likes it, and which of those add-backs you would and would not accept as an analyst.$x$, $x$["Cash EPS adds back non-cash charges to GAAP EPS", "Common add-backs: acquired intangible amortization, SBC, impairments", "Management prefers it post-deal because intangible amort depresses GAAP", "Acquired intangible amortization add-back defensible if no maintenance capex", "Reject adding back SBC - real economic cost / dilution", "Scrutinize recurring restructuring dressed as one-time", "Tax-effect the add-backs / watch share count denominator"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Cash EPS starts from GAAP EPS and adds back non-cash charges - most often amortization of acquired intangibles, stock-based comp, and sometimes impairments or deal costs - then divides by the share count. Management of a serial acquirer loves it because every deal creates a big slug of intangible amortization that crushes GAAP earnings even though it requires no ongoing cash, so cash EPS lets them argue the underlying business is healthier than GAAP shows. As an analyst I split the add-backs. Amortization of acquired customer relationships or technology I am usually willing to add back, provided the company is not quietly spending cash to replace those intangibles - if they have to keep buying customers, it is a real cost. What I refuse to add back is stock-based comp, because it is a genuine economic expense that dilutes me as a shareholder whether or not cash leaves the building. I also push back on restructuring that recurs every year. And I make sure the add-backs are tax-effected and that the denominator includes dilution, otherwise cash EPS flatters twice over.$x$),
(1974, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Net Income To FCF Bridge$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company reports 500 of net income but only 150 of free cash flow. Take me through how you bridge net income to free cash flow, and tell me where the gaps most often hide a lower-quality earnings story.$x$, $x$["Start NI, add back D&A and non-cash charges (SBC, impairments)", "Subtract working capital build (receivables/inventory up, payables down)", "Subtract capex (and capitalized software/dev) to reach FCF", "Deferred taxes and other non-cash items reconcile NI to CFO", "Red flag: persistent working capital drag funding reported growth", "Red flag: capex far below D&A or opex capitalized off the P&L", "Quantify bridge: 500 NI down to 150 FCF means 350 of leakage"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I build the bridge in three blocks. Start with net income of 500, then add back the non-cash charges - depreciation and amortization, stock-based comp, any impairments or deferred tax movement - which gets me toward cash from operations. Next I subtract the working capital change: if receivables and inventory build or payables shrink, cash gets trapped on the balance sheet even though the income statement already booked the profit. Then I subtract capex, including capitalized software and development, to land on free cash flow. With 500 of net income converting to only 150 of FCF, I have 350 of leakage and I want to know where it sits. A persistent working capital drag is my first worry, because it usually means growth is being funded with receivables the company has not collected - low-quality revenue. My second worry runs the other way: operating costs being capitalized to flatter the P&L, or capex sitting far below depreciation, which signals underinvestment that borrows from the future to look healthy today. Healthy businesses convert most of net income to cash; a wide, recurring gap is where the earnings-quality story hides.$x$),
(1975, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Channel Stuffing And Bill-And-Hold$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A consumer-products company posts a big revenue beat in its fiscal Q4. What specific signs in the numbers would make you suspect channel stuffing or a bill-and-hold arrangement, and what does ASC 606 require before revenue can be recognized in a genuine bill-and-hold?$x$, $x$["Q4/period-end revenue spike with receivables rising faster", "DSO jump / returns reserve rising / subsequent-quarter air pocket", "Channel stuffing: pushing excess product to distributors to pull sales forward", "Bill-and-hold: revenue booked but goods still held by seller", "ASC 606: substantive reason, goods identified/separated, ready to transfer, seller cannot use or redirect", "Control must transfer to customer despite physical possession", "Watch generous return rights / extended payment terms"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The pattern that triggers me is a revenue surge right at period end, especially fiscal year end, where receivables climb faster than sales and days sales outstanding jumps - that says product went out the door but cash did not, so the company may have pushed inventory onto distributors to pull future sales forward. I also watch the returns reserve and the very next quarter: channel stuffing typically leaves an air pocket because the channel is already full. Generous return rights or stretched payment terms granted late in the quarter are tells, since they are bribes to take product early. Bill-and-hold is the cousin where the company books the sale but the goods never physically leave its warehouse. ASC 606 sets a high bar before that counts: there must be a substantive business reason for the arrangement, the goods must be separately identified as the customer's, they must be ready for physical transfer, and the seller cannot have the ability to use the product or redirect it to anyone else. In short, control has to genuinely pass to the buyer even though the seller still holds the inventory, otherwise it is just premature revenue.$x$),
(1976, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Capitalize Versus Expense Lever$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Two competitors spend the same on software development, but one capitalizes most of it and the other expenses it. Walk me through how this distorts comparability across the income statement, EBITDA, and cash flow, and how you would normalize the two to compare them fairly.$x$, $x$["Capitalizer shows higher current earnings and margins, amortizes later", "Expenser takes full hit now, lower near-term margin", "EBITDA diverges: capitalized spend becomes amort below the line, flatters EBITDA", "Cash flow: capitalizer pushes spend into investing (CFI), inflates CFO", "Free cash flow is the great equalizer - both pay the same cash", "Normalize: treat capitalized dev as expense or use FCF / EBITDA less capex", "Watch capitalization creep as an earnings lever"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Same cash out the door, very different optics. The capitalizer records an asset and only expenses it slowly through amortization, so its current earnings and margins look higher, while the expenser takes the whole hit now and looks less profitable even though the businesses are identical. The distortion is worst at EBITDA: the capitalizer's spend becomes amortization that sits below the EBITDA line, so its EBITDA is structurally inflated, whereas the expenser's development cost is baked into operating expenses and drags EBITDA down. Cash flow compounds it - the capitalizer routes the spend through investing as capex, which lifts cash from operations, while the expenser's identical spend reduces CFO. The equalizer is free cash flow, because both hand over the same cash regardless of accounting. So to compare them fairly I either treat the capitalized development as expensed, pulling it back into operating costs and out of capex, or I move both down to EBITDA less capex or to FCF. I also watch for capitalization creep, because a rising capitalization rate is a classic way to manufacture margin.$x$),
(1977, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Organic Versus Acquired Growth$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A roll-up reports 20 percent revenue growth and management calls the business a strong organic grower. How do acquisitive companies flatter organic growth, and what would you do to strip the deals out and find the true underlying growth rate?$x$, $x$["Headline growth mixes acquired revenue with organic", "M&A revenue counts for ~12 months then rolls into the base", "Tricks: inconsistent organic definitions, selective divestiture exclusion, stub-period games", "Pro forma / same-store or like-for-like is the honest lens", "Normalize: compare only businesses owned in both periods", "Check cash acquisition spend and goodwill growth versus organic claims", "Watch margin and ROIC dilution from serial dealmaking"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Headline growth at a roll-up blends two very different things: revenue the company actually grew and revenue it simply bought. An acquisition contributes a full slug of sales for roughly twelve months and only rolls into the comparable base after it has been owned in both periods, so a company that keeps buying can show high total growth indefinitely while the underlying business barely moves. The flattery comes from loose definitions - management picks what counts as organic, may keep contribution from recent deals in the organic bucket, selectively excludes divestitures, or plays with stub periods around the close date. To find the truth I strip it to a like-for-like or same-store basis: compare only the businesses owned in both the current and prior period, exclude anything acquired or sold in between, and adjust for currency. I cross-check the story against the cash flow statement and the goodwill line - if they are spending heavily on acquisitions and goodwill is ballooning, the growth is bought, not organic. And I watch margins and returns on capital, because serial acquirers often dilute both even as the top line grows.$x$),
(1978, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Non-GAAP Adjustment Games$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A software company's adjusted EBITDA is roughly double its GAAP operating income, and the gap keeps widening each year. Walk me through the adjustments that typically drive that wedge, which ones are legitimate, and how you would pressure-test the adjusted number in diligence.$x$, $x$["Common add-backs: SBC, restructuring, acquisition costs, litigation, impairments", "SBC largest and most aggressive add-back for software", "Legitimate: truly non-recurring, genuinely non-operating items", "Suspect: recurring restructuring, run-rate/pro forma synergies, capitalized labor", "Widening gap over time signals adjustment creep", "Pressure-test: build own bridge GAAP to adjusted, question each add-back", "Anchor on GAAP and FCF, reject SBC add-back for valuation"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A two-times gap that keeps widening is itself a warning. The usual wedge is built from stock-based comp, restructuring, acquisition and integration costs, litigation, and impairments, plus sometimes run-rate synergies the company has not actually realized. For software, stock-based comp is by far the biggest and most aggressive piece, because it can be a huge share of the cost base and management treats it as free. I sort the add-backs into legitimate and suspect. Genuinely non-recurring or non-operating items - a one-off legal settlement, a discrete impairment - I am comfortable adjusting. What I push back on is anything that recurs: restructuring every single year is just operating cost, pro forma synergies are aspirational, and capitalized labor quietly removes real expense. The widening gap tells me adjustment creep is the story. To pressure-test it I rebuild the bridge line by line from GAAP operating income to adjusted EBITDA and challenge each add-back for recurrence and economic substance. Ultimately I anchor on GAAP and free cash flow, and for valuation I keep stock-based comp as a real cost rather than letting it vanish.$x$),
(1979, NULL, 'primary', $x$Accounting$x$, $x$Cash Flow Statement Forensics$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Give me the things you look for on the cash flow statement specifically to catch a business that is quietly deteriorating even while the income statement still looks fine. Walk me through the lines and the relationships, not just one ratio.$x$, $x$["CFO versus net income - falling conversion is the core signal", "Quality of CFO: earnings-driven vs stretching payables / squeezing working capital", "Capex versus D&A - underinvestment borrows from the future", "Capitalized items inflating CFO while draining CFI", "Rising debt or equity issuance in financing funding operations or dividends", "Dividends/buybacks exceeding FCF - unsustainable returns", "One-time working capital boosts or factoring receivables flattering CFO"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The income statement is where management has the most discretion, so I use the cash flow statement as the lie detector. I start with cash from operations against net income - if conversion is steadily falling, the earnings are getting softer even if reported profit holds up. Then I interrogate the quality of that operating cash: is it coming from the business, or from stretching payables, squeezing inventory, or factoring receivables, which give a one-time boost that cannot repeat. I compare capex to depreciation, because a company that consistently spends less than it depreciates is underinvesting and borrowing from its future to look healthy today. I watch for costs being capitalized, which lifts operating cash while quietly draining investing. Then I move to financing: if debt or equity issuance is rising to plug the gap, or if dividends and buybacks exceed free cash flow, the shareholder returns are being funded by the balance sheet rather than the business. None of these is a single ratio - it is the pattern across the three sections, and a deteriorating business usually shows it in cash long before it shows it in earnings.$x$);
